{{Distinguish|private sector|division (business)}} {{Expert-subject|Economics |date=May 2009}} {{Economic sectors}}
In [[economics]], the '''business sector''' or '''corporate sector''' - sometimes popularly called simply "'''business'''" - is "the part of the [[economy]] made up by [[company|companies]]".<ref>Longman Business English Dictionary</ref> It is a subset of the [[Sovereign state|domestic]] [[economy]],<ref> But compare {{cite book | last1 = Keese | first1 = Mark | last2 = Salou | first2 = Gérard | last3 = Richardson | first3 = Pete | title = The measurement of output and factors of production for the business sector in OECD countries: the OECD business sector database | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Zzm5AAAAIAAJ | series = OECD Department of Economics and Statistics working papers | volume = 95-101 | issue = 99 | publisher = Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development | publication-date = 1991 | page = i | accessdate = 2015-06-07 | quote = [...] recent work of the OECD Economics and Statistics Department to construct an international Business Sector Data Base (BSDB) for use in a wide variety of analyses of production and supply issues [...]. }} </ref> excluding the economic activities of general [[government]], of private households, and of [[non-profit organization]]s serving individuals.<ref name="uslabor">{{cite web |url = http://www.bls.gov/bls/glossary.htm |title = BLS Information |date= February 28, 2008|work= Glossary|publisher= U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics Division of Information Services |accessdate= 2009-05-05}}</ref> An alternative analysis of economies, the [[three-sector theory]], subdivides them into:{{cn|date=June 2015}}
* the [[primary sector of the economy | primary sector]] (producing raw materials) * the [[secondary sector of the economy | secondary sector]] (carrying out manufacturing) * the [[tertiary sector of the economy | tertiary sector]] (providing sales and services)
In the [[United States]] the business sector accounted for about 78 percent of the value of gross domestic product (GDP) {{as of | 2000 | lc = on}}.<ref name="uslabor"/> [[Kuwait]] and [[Tuvalu]] each had business sectors accounting for less than 40% of GDP {{as of | 2015 | lc = on}}.<ref> {{cite book | chapter = 1: Overview: Opportunities and challenges for Myanmar | title = OECD Development Pathways Multi-dimensional Review of Myanmar | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=kHKADAAAQBAJ | volume = 3: From Analysis to Action | location = Paris | publisher = OECD Publishing | publication-date = 2016 | page = 29 | isbn = 9789264256545 | access-date = 2017-12-27 | quote = The countries that have general government revenue more than 60% of GDP are Kiribati, Kuwait, Lesotho, Micronesia and Tuvalu. Source: IMF (2015), World Economic Outlook (database), International Monetary Fund. }} </ref>
